An event defines a process that is triggered in response to user interaction with a component (such as a button) or the occurrence of a specific event. This event, which is associated with a function or procedure, is automatically executed when triggered. This ensures that quick and efficient responses can be made to user interactions.<br>

For developers working with Clomosy, event management is an important technique for effectively handling user interactions. Using events effectively will help make your application more dynamic and user-friendly.<br>

There are two different methods for handling events:<br>

<h2>Standard Event Binding Method</h2>
This is the most common and traditional form of event binding. Here, a component (e.g., TclButton) is directly assigned to a specific event (e.g., OnClick) by linking it to a procedure.<br>


<b><i>Use of Example:</i></b><br>
<pre>
Button1.OnClick = 'Button1OnClick'; // void Button1OnClick
</pre>

<h3> Control Events </h3>

<div class="table-responsive">
{| class="wikitable" style="border: 2px solid #c3d7e0"
! style="background-color: #c3d7e0"| Feature  !!style="background-color: #c3d7e0"| Definition
|-
|OnClick|| This event occurs when a button click action is triggered. This is usually the most basic event and allows the user to initiate an action.
|-
| OnDblClick || An event used to capture the double-click action of a component. This event is triggered when the user quickly clicks on a component twice.
|-
| OnResize || It is an event triggered when the size of a component is changed. For example, it is used during the resizing of a button.
|-
|OnEnter || This event is triggered when a component is focused (selected with the keyboard or clicked with the mouse). This is especially important for keyboard navigation and interaction.
|-
|OnExit || This event is commonly used for actions that need to be performed when exiting a input field, such as when transitioning from one component to another.
|-
|OnChange|| This event is triggered when the value of a component changes. It is commonly used in components that can be modified by the user, such as input fields.
|-
|OnTimer|| This event occurs when a timer component (usually [[TClTimer| TClTimer]]) is triggered. It is used to perform tasks that are repeated at specific intervals.
|-
| OnMouseDown || It is an event triggered when a component (such as a button or an image) is clicked with the mouse. This event occurs when the mouse button is pressed. See [[Mouse_Movements | page ]] for more information.
|-
| OnMouseUp || It is an event triggered when a component is released after being clicked with the mouse. This event represents the moment when the mouse button is released. See [[Mouse_Movements | page ]] for more information.
|-
| OnMouseMove || It is an event triggered when you move the mouse pointer over a component. This event occurs when you move the mouse pointer. See [[Mouse_Movements | page ]] for more information.
|}
</div>

<b>Example</b><br>
Various event operations are performed in response to user interactions. For example, clicking the button (Btn1OnClick) or double-clicking it (Btn1OnDblClick), focusing on the text box (Edt1OnEnter), changing the text (Edt1OnChange), resizing the button (Btn1OnResize), and exiting the text box (Edt1OnExit) dynamically update the properties of the relevant components. Additionally, events such as mouse movement (onFormMouseMove), mouse down (onFormMouseDown), and mouse up (onFormMouseUp) alter the opacity of images. The timer (GetTimerShow) changes the image size each time it is triggered.<br>

<pre>
Var   
  Form1 : TclForm;
  Btn1 : TClProButton;
  Edt1 : TclEdit;
  GetTimer: TClTimer;
  InfLbl : TclLabel;
  RotateImg : TclImage;
  isActive : Boolean;

void Btn1OnClick;
{
  Btn1.clProSettings.BackgroundColor = clAlphaColor.clHexToColor('#1c4c94');
  Btn1.SetclProSettings(Btn1.clProSettings);
  Btn1.Height = 120;
  Btn1.Text = 'Double Click..';
}
void Btn1OnDblClick;
{
  Btn1.clProSettings.BackgroundColor = clAlphaColor.clHexToColor('#e3b36b');
  Btn1.SetclProSettings(Btn1.clProSettings);
  Btn1.Height = 80;
  Btn1.Text = 'Click Once..';
}
void Edt1OnEnter;
{
  Edt1.Text = '';
}
void Edt1OnChange;
{
  InfLbl.Text = 'Size of the Edit object : '+IntToStr(Length(Edt1.Text));
}
void Btn1OnResize;
{
  InfLbl.Text = 'Button size changed';
}

void Edt1OnExit;
{
  if (Edt1.Text == '')
    InfLbl.Text = 'Edit field was left empty';
  else
    InfLbl.Text = 'Are you sure about the text you entered in the Edit field?';
}
void onFormMouseMove;
{
  InfLbl.Text = 'Mouse Position: X=' + IntToStr(Form1.clFormMousePosX) + ' Y=' + IntToStr(Form1.clFormMousePosY);
  InfLbl.Text = 'Mouse Position: X=' + IntToStr(Form1.clSenderMousePosX) + ' Y=' + IntToStr(Form1.clSenderMousePosY);
}
void onFormMouseDown;
{
  RotateImg.Opacity = 0.5;
}

void onFormMouseUp;
{ 
  RotateImg.Opacity = 1.0;
} 
void GetTimerShow;
{
  if isActive
  {
    RotateImg.Height = Form1.clHeight / 2.5;
    RotateImg.Width = Form1.clWidth / 2.5;
  }else{
    RotateImg.Height = Form1.clHeight / 1.5;
    RotateImg.Width = Form1.clWidth / 1.5;
  }
  isActive = not isActive;
}
{
  isActive = True;
  Form1 = TclForm.Create(Self);
  InfLbl = Form1.AddNewLabel(Form1,'InfLbl','{Information}');
  InfLbl.Align = AlMostTop;
  InfLbl.WordWrap = True;
  InfLbl.AutoSize = True;

  Edt1 = Form1.AddNewEdit(Form1,'Edt1','Please write something...');
  Edt1.Align = alTop;
  Edt1.Margins.Top = 10;
  Edt1.Height = 40;
  Edt1.OnEnter = 'Edt1OnEnter'; 
  Edt1.OnChange = 'Edt1OnChange'; 
  Edt1.OnExit = 'Edt1OnExit'; 

  RotateImg = Form1.AddNewImage(Form1,'RotateImg');
  RotateImg.Align = AlCenter;
  RotateImg.Height = Form1.clHeight / 1.5;
  RotateImg.Width = Form1.clWidth / 1.5;
  Form1.SetImage(RotateImg,'https://clomosy.com/demos/star4.png');
  RotateImg.OnMouseDown = 'onFormMouseDown';
  RotateImg.OnMouseUp = 'onFormMouseUp';
  RotateImg.OnMouseMove = 'onFormMouseMove';

  Btn1 = Form1.AddNewProButton(Form1,'Btn1','Click');
  Btn1.Align = alBottom;
  Btn1.Height = 80;
  Btn1.clProSettings.BackgroundColor = clAlphaColor.clHexToColor('#3dc285');
  Btn1.SetclProSettings(Btn1.clProSettings);
  Btn1.OnClick = 'Btn1OnClick'; 
  Btn1.OnDblClick = 'Btn1OnDblClick'; 
  Btn1.OnResize = 'Btn1OnResize'; 

  GetTimer= Form1.AddNewTimer(Form1,'GetTimer',300); 
  GetTimer.Enabled = True;
  GetTimer.OnTimer = 'GetTimerShow'; 

  Form1.Run;
}
</pre>



<h2>Dynamic Event Addition Method</h2>
This method provides a more flexible way to bind events. Using a method like AddNewEvent, events can be assigned at runtime. In other words, the assignment and execution of events can be determined dynamically while the application is running.<br>


<b><i>Use of Example:</i></b><br>
<pre>
Form1.AddNewEvent(Button1,tbeOnClick,'Button1OnClick'); // void Button1OnClick
</pre>

